ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's
 a great position to be in. You already have a warm relationship there, 
you were shortlisted, and you share a cultural connection — that's a 
genuinely strong foundation.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Asking
 for feedback is the right call because it's low pressure but keeps you 
on his radar, and if the project is good it speaks for itself without 
you having to say "please hire me."</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The
 Greek connection is worth leaning into slightly too — not in a forced 
way, but it naturally makes the conversation more personal and memorable
 than a standard candidate follow-up.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">How long ago were you shortlisted? And do you know if the role was filled or if there might be future openings?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
