ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This is a really strong profile — honestly above average for early career. A few things stand out:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Your genuine differentiators:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The NHS/healthcare 
background gives you pattern recognition and stakeholder communication 
that pure football analysts rarely have</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Off-ball movement as a niche is well-timed — the industry is moving that direction</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">You've already been shortlisted at SkillCorner, which validates the profile isn't just on paper</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>On your next project</strong>, given your target is data companies specifically, I'd go in this direction:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Build a "run quality model" that extends your flagship project.</strong>
 Take the A-League work further by adding a predictive or comparative 
layer — e.g. which run types in which phases generate the most xThreat 
per 90, and build a player-facing dashboard in Streamlit that lets you 
compare profiles. SkillCorner's actual product is essentially this — 
interactive, interpretable, tracking-derived intelligence.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This works because it shows you can go <em>deeper</em> on one thing rather than sideways, which is what a research analyst role actually requires day to day.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What I'd hold off on for now:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Another clustering project (you already have one)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Anything too broad or top-5-league generic — your niche is your strength</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The
 SkillCorner recruiter feedback will be gold here too — whatever gap he 
identifies, make that your next project. Timing it that way is smart.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Have you had a response from him yet?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
