ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This is a smart sequencing decision. Here's why this project first makes sense:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>It bridges your CV and your portfolio.</strong>
 You mention the Portland Thorns experience in applications but don't 
have a public artifact that shows what that work actually looked like. 
This fills that gap immediately.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>It's the most "hireable" project you can build right now.</strong>
 Data companies and clubs both want to see that you can produce 
something a coach would actually use — not just a Jupyter notebook with 
plots. A professional opposition report does exactly that.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>It sets up the RDI project perfectly.</strong>
 Transitions and regains are central to this analysis, so by the time 
you build the Transition Trigger, you'll have already done the 
groundwork on how to detect and frame those moments.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>One honest challenge to flag:</strong>
The IMPECT dataset — do you actually have access to it, or are you 
planning to simulate that style of analysis with a different dataset? 
That's the key practical question before you start. If you're using 
StatsBomb open data and framing it as "IMPECT-style," just make sure 
your positioning language is precise. Your disclaimer section already 
handles this well.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The output format is the most important decision here.</strong> Are you thinking:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A PDF report (most coach-friendly, most impressive visually)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A GitHub README with embedded visuals</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A Streamlit dashboard</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">What dataset do you actually have access to for this one?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
