ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">No, it was not a mistake at all. Let me be very clear about this.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What you did was correct for a first project.</strong>
 Analysing all runs across all phases is a completely valid starting 
point — it gives you the full picture before you start slicing. Most 
entry-level analysts never even get to the phase-of-play question. You 
did.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What he's doing is not criticising you.</strong>
 He's a recruiter at a data company asking PhD-level follow-up questions
 to see how you think. That's a good sign — you don't probe projects 
you're not interested in.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The two questions he raised are "next step" questions</strong>, not "you did it wrong" questions. The difference is important:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">❌ "You shouldn't have used xThreat" — that would be criticism</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">✅ "Have you thought about the 10-second horizon limitation?" — that's curiosity about depth</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What your reply will show him</strong>
 is the most important thing — that you understand your own methodology 
deeply enough to recognise its limitations and already know what you'd 
do next. That's senior analyst thinking, not entry-level.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The honest truth:</strong>
 he wrote back in Greek, said "bravo," called it good work, and gave you
 constructive questions. That is not the response of someone who thinks 
you made a mistake. That is the response of someone who is quietly 
mentoring you.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Reply confidently.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
