ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's actually stronger than the RDI concept we discussed earlier. Here's why:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Your metric is better because:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It's grounded in something measurable and concrete — ball progression after regain</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">5-second window is more defensible than the 8-second RDI window</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Forward/lateral movement adds a directional quality dimension</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It connects directly to your existing Regain → Progression Pipeline project, showing depth not just breadth</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What it measures in plain language:</strong>
<em>"How quickly and effectively does a team turn defence into attack in the first 5 seconds after winning the ball back?"</em></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's a question every coach wants answered.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What I'd call it:</strong>
Instead of RDI, something like:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Transition Efficiency Index (TEI)</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Progressive Transition Score (PTS)</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Regain-to-Progression Score (RPS)</strong></li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Simple, self-explanatory, professional.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The Argentina angle fits perfectly</strong> because their 2022 World Cup transitions were tactically fascinating — controlled, direct, Messi-triggered counter attacks.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>One question before you start building:</strong>
Is your existing Regain → Progression project already coded in Python 
with this logic, or are you starting fresh with the StatsBomb World Cup 
data?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
