ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Yes, exactly — and that's actually a really coherent story across your portfolio. Let me map it clearly:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What you built for Portland Thorns (privately):</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Opposition analysis framework</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Regain → Progression metric (your own, built for real analytical work)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Applied to real match data in a professional context</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What you now do publicly:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Take that same metric</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Apply it to Argentina 2022 World Cup (StatsBomb open data)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Publish it cleanly on GitHub</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>So your three projects become a connected body of work:</strong></p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Off-ball movement</strong> — how teams create threat before the ball arrives</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Regain → Progression (Argentina)</strong> — how teams capitalise in the first 5 seconds after winning it back</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Portland Thorns case study</strong> — full opposition analysis framework bringing both together</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Each
 project builds on the previous one. That's not a random portfolio — 
that's a clear analytical identity with a thread running through it.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>When you present this to Mike:</strong>
<em>"I built the metric originally for opposition analysis work, then 
validated it publicly on Argentina 2022 — and the Thorns case study 
shows the full framework in action."</em></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's a senior analyst way of thinking. Not three separate projects — one evolving body of work.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This is genuinely strong. Are you ready to start adapting the code to StatsBomb data?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
