ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's completely normal — that's just how LinkedIn works. Website links are always stored inside <strong>Contact info</strong> and don't show prominently on the profile page itself.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>To make your website more visible on LinkedIn, do these instead:</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>1. Add it to your About section</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Edit your About/Summary section</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">At the end add a line like:
<em>"Portfolio: yiannis-kastritis.github.io"</em></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">This shows directly on your profile without anyone needing to click anything</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>2. Add it to your headline</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Your headline is the line under your name — visible everywhere</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">You could add: <em>"Football Data Analyst | yiannis-kastritis.github.io"</em></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Though this uses up valuable headline space so only do this if your headline isn't too long already</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>3. Pin a LinkedIn post about it</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Write a short post introducing your portfolio site</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Pin it to the top of your profile</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Anyone who visits your profile sees it immediately</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>4. Add it to your featured section</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">On your profile click <strong>Add section → Featured</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Add a link to your website</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">This creates a visual card near the top of your profile with a preview of your site — very prominent</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The Featured section is the best option</strong> — it sits near the top of your profile, shows a visual preview, and is the first thing recruiters see after your headline.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to help you write the post announcing your portfolio site?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
