ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's completely normal — it's not a bug, it's just how free Streamlit hosting works.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Why it happens:</strong>
Streamlit's free tier puts your app to "sleep" after it hasn't been 
visited for a while — usually 7 days of inactivity. When someone visits,
 it needs to "wake up" which takes about 30–60 seconds.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The problem for your portfolio:</strong>
If Mike or a recruiter clicks your Streamlit link and sees a loading 
screen, some will wait — but many won't. First impressions matter.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Your options:</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 1 — Just warn people (easiest)</strong>
Add a note in your README and LinkedIn description:
<em>"Note: the app may take 30 seconds to wake up on first visit — please wait."</em>
Honest and sets expectations.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 2 — Keep it alive yourself (free)</strong>
Visit your own app every few days to prevent it sleeping. Simple but requires you to remember.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 3 — Upgrade to Streamlit Community Cloud (still free)</strong>
Make sure you're using Streamlit Community Cloud properly — go to 
share.streamlit.io, sign in with GitHub, and check your app settings. 
Sometimes redeploying fixes persistent sleep issues.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option 4 — Add a loading message to the app itself</strong>
Add a spinner or welcome message inside the app code so the wake-up period feels intentional rather than broken.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>My honest recommendation:</strong>
Do Option 1 and Option 2 together for now. When the Argentina project is
 done and you're actively sharing links with recruiters, visit the app 
yourself every couple of days to keep it warm.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to update the Streamlit description on your website and LinkedIn to include the wake-up warning?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
