ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great
 progress! For the photo on your LinkedIn Featured section, LinkedIn 
automatically tries to generate a preview image from the website URL — 
but sometimes it doesn't look great.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>To get a nicer preview image for your portfolio link on LinkedIn:</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">You need to add a special image to your website called an <strong>Open Graph image</strong> — this is what LinkedIn, Twitter etc. use as the preview thumbnail when you share a link.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Let me create one for you. But first:</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
