<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Step 1 — Save it as an image</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Right click on the image above → <strong>Save image as</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Save it as <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">og-image.png</code></li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Step 2 — Add it to your website</strong>
Upload <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">og-image.png</code> to your GitHub repo alongside your <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">index.html</code>, then I'll add these lines to your website's <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">&lt;head&gt;</code> section which tell LinkedIn to use it as the preview:</p>
