ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Good instinct to question that. Honest answer:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>SkillCorner — yes, appropriate</strong>
You used their open data directly and they're aware of it. Mike even 
gave you feedback on the project. It's publicly available data and 
you've credited them properly. Including it is fine.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>StatsBomb — yes, appropriate</strong>
Their open data is specifically released for exactly this kind of 
portfolio and educational work. They actively encourage analysts to use 
it and share projects publicly. Including it is fine.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The key distinction:</strong>
You're not claiming to work for them or be affiliated with them. You're 
showing which data sources you work with — which is standard practice in
 football analytics portfolios. It's like a developer listing which APIs
 they've worked with.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>One small tweak I'd make though:</strong>
Instead of showing the company names as badges, I'd change the wording slightly to make the context clearer. Instead of just <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">SKILLCORNER</code> and <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">STATSBOMB</code>, something like:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">SKILLCORNER DATA</code></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">STATSBOMB OPEN DATA</code></li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That
 tiny addition makes it clear you used their open/public data rather 
than implying a formal partnership or employment relationship.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Bottom line:</strong>
 Keep them both. They're credible names that signal you work with real 
industry data sources — exactly what a company like SkillCorner wants to
 see.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to update the image with that small wording change?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
